Add use case for deleting tag

As a counterpart to the tagging command, this command untags a user from
some tags.

This implementation can do multiple tags at the same time to amke
removing tags faster. It throws an error on non matching tags, but that
can be changed if that is not desirable e.g. if batch operations are
introduced.

Find was a rudimentary keyword search over the user names, which suits
its name. The new funcitonality on the other hand is meant to be more
generic, operating on every component of the `Person`, with more
flexibility of matching.

Therefore, the command has been renamed to `filter`.

To make the filter command as abstract as possible, it will work on a
predicate on `Person` that will handle extraction and
manipulation of the `Person`'s values inside itself.

Make ComponentPredicate extensible to other kinds

commitResults.messageBody:
The `Component` enum was previously duplicated in the respective
predicate types. The predicates handled the component extraction from
`Person` and were needed to be handled differently by the
`FilterCommandParser`.

To fix this, the `Component` enum has been moved to `Person` along with
the extraction logic. This removes the violation of the Law of Demeter
from the extraction code and removes the dependency of the
`FilterCommandParser` from every type to just `Person`.

`ComponentExistencePredicate`'s constructor now throws an error if given
an unsupported component to accomodate the generalising of the
`Component` code. This will also make error reporting on unsupported
components more cohesive as every class handles their own error.
